<item>
            <title>[HTTPCLIENT-128] Redirection of a POST method</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HTTPCLIENT-128</link>
                <project id="12310360" key="HTTPCLIENT">HttpComponents HttpClient</project>
                        <description>I execute a PostMethod to an URL which redirects me to a HTML page. If I set &lt;br/&gt;
follow redirects to true the HttpClient wants to execute once more a POST. Of &lt;br/&gt;
course a POST is not allowed to HTML pages. I think the HttpClient should &lt;br/&gt;
exectue a GET method instead. That&amp;#39;s also what is in the RFC2616:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
10.3 Redirection 3xx&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This class of status code indicates that further action needs to be&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;taken by the user agent in order to fulfill the request.  The action&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;required MAY be carried out by the user agent without interaction&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;with the user if and only if the method used in the second request is&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;GET or HEAD. A client SHOULD detect infinite redirection loops, since&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;such loops generate network traffic for each redirection.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Note: previous versions of this specification recommended a&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;maximum of five redirections. Content developers should be aware&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;that there might be clients that implement such a fixed&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;limitation.</description>
                <environment>Operating System: All&lt;br/&gt;
Platform: All</environment>
