                                                    <comments>
                    <comment id="12379733" author="oleg.kalnichevski@bearingpoint.com" created="Thu, 21 Nov 2002 23:20:58 +0000"  >I strongly disagree it&amp;#39;s HttpClient&amp;#39;s responsibility to check what type of URL &lt;br/&gt;
a request is redirected to. I do not think the HttpClient should take liberty &lt;br/&gt;
in changing a request type, matter how appropriate that might seem at the first &lt;br/&gt;
glance. This kind of decision should better be taken on a higher level, that &lt;br/&gt;
is, by the HttpClient consumer</comment>
                    <comment id="12379734" author="toemmi" created="Thu, 21 Nov 2002 23:41:50 +0000"  >I agree with you that the HttpClient should not check what kind of URL the &lt;br/&gt;
redirect is. But please take once more a look to the RFC (10.3 Redirection &lt;br/&gt;
3xx). The second request (forwarded method) can only be a GET or HEAD. POST is &lt;br/&gt;
not allowed.</comment>
                    <comment id="12379735" author="oleg.kalnichevski@bearingpoint.com" created="Sat, 1 Feb 2003 08:15:56 +0000"  >Entity enclosing methods now disallow automatic redirection</comment>
